<section xml:id="section-introduction-to-absolute-value-functions">

    <title>Introduction to Absolute Value Functions</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>This section will introduce the basic concepts behind absolute value functions and their graphs. This information will be useful at the end of this chapter when we solve absolute value equations and inequalities.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube=""/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Definition of Absolute Value</title>
        <p>Recall that in the <xref ref="section-absolute-value-and-square-root" text="title">absolute value and square root section</xref>, we defined the <term>absolute value</term> of a number to be the distance between that number and <m>0</m> on a number line. Also recall that this causes the output of the absolute value function to never be a negative number since we are under the presumption that <q>distance</q> is always positive (or 0).</p>

        <example>
            <p><ol label="a.">
                <li>
                    <p>Since the number <m>5</m> is <m>5</m> units from <m>0</m>, then <m>\abs{5}=5</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Since the number <m>-3</m> is <m>3</m> units from <m>0</m>, then <m>\abs{-3}=3</m>.</p>
                </li>
            </ol></p>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p> Yonas takes a <m>5</m>-block walk north from his home to a food cart. After enjoying dinner, he then walks <m>9</m> blocks south of the food cart to his favorite movie theater.</p>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>How many blocks has Yonas walked in total when he reaches the theater?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>How many blocks is Yonas from home when he reaches the theater?</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>Since we only care about total distance, we can ignore the <q>signs</q> on the distances walked (either north or south) and simply add the two values together. Mathematically, if we think of north as positive values and south as having negative values, this situation is the same as
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\abs{5}+\abs{-9}\amp=5+9</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=14</mrow>
                           </md>
                       Yonas walked a total of <m>14</m> blocks when he reached the theater.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>When he reaches the theater, Yonas's actual position could be thought of as <m>5-9</m> or <m>5+(-9)</m>. But the actual distance from the theater to his home is better thought of as:<md>
                            <mrow>\abs{5+(-9)}\amp=\abs{-4}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=4</mrow>
                        </md>Yonas was <m>4</m> blocks from home when he reached the theater.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Evaluating Absolute Value Functions</title>
        <p>The formula <m>f(x)=\abs{x}</m> does describe a function because no matter what number you input for <m>x</m>, there is only one measured distance from <m>0</m> to that value <m>x</m>.</p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Let <m>f(x)=\abs{x}</m> and <m>g(x)=\abs{2x-5}</m>. Evaluate the following expressions.</p>
                <p><ol label="a." cols="5">
                    <li><m>f(34)</m></li>
                    <li><m>f(-63)</m></li>
                    <li><m>f(0)</m></li>
                    <li><m>g(13)</m></li>
                    <li><m>g(1)</m></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>f(\highlight{34})\amp=\abs{\highlight{34}}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=34</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>f(\highlight{-63})\amp=\abs{\highlight{-63}}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=63</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>f(\highlight{0})\amp=\abs{\highlight{0}}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=0</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>g(\highlight{13})\amp=\abs{2\cdot\highlight{13}-5}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{21}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=21</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>g(\highlight{1})\amp=\abs{2\cdot\highlight{1}-5}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{-3}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=3</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        $true=PopUp(['?',"True","False"],1);
                        $false=PopUp(['?',"True","False"],2);
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>Mark each equation as True or False.<ol label="a.">
                        <li>
                            <p><var name="$true" form="popup" /> <m>\abs{10}=10</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><var name="$false" form="popup" /> <m>\abs{-3}</m> is both <m>3</m> and <m>-3</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><var name="$false" form="popup" /> <m>\abs{x+4}=x+4</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><var name="$true" form="popup" /> <m>\abs{-6}=\abs{6}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><var name="$false" form="popup" /> <m>\abs{x-3}=\abs{x+3}</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Remember that to be <q>false</q> when there is a variable in the equation, all that has to occur is a single input number that makes the equation false.</p>
                    <p><ol label="a.">
                        <li>
                            <p>True: <m>\abs{10}=10</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>False: <m>\abs{-3}</m> is only <m>3</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>False: <m>\abs{x+4}\neq x+4</m> for many values of <m>x</m>. When you have to decide whether or not an equation is true, one good method to help you decide is to plug in a few numbers to see if each number makes the equation true or false. Be sure to pick a variety and input at least two numbers, if not three. In this case, we will choose <m>10</m> and <m>-20</m>.</p>

                            <p>When <m>x=\substitute{10}</m>:<md>
                                <mrow>\abs{x+4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}x+4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\abs{\substitute{10}+4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\substitute{10}+4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\abs{14}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}14</mrow>
                                <mrow>14\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}14</mrow>
                            </md></p>

                            <p>When <m>x=\substitute{-20}</m>:<md>
                                <mrow>\abs{x+4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}x+4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\abs{\substitute{-20}+4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\substitute{-20}+4</mrow>
                                <mrow>\abs{-16}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-16</mrow>
                                <mrow>16\amp\neq-16</mrow>
                            </md></p>

                            <p>When we input <m>-20</m>, the equation was false, which indicates that the equation <m>\abs{x+4}=x+4</m> is false for general <m>x</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>True: <m>\abs{-6}=\abs{6}</m>. Both <m>\abs{-6}</m> and <m>\abs{6}</m> are equal to <m>6</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>False: <m>\abs{x-3}\neq\abs{x+3}</m>. Again we should choose some numbers to check the validity of the equation. We will choose <m>-12</m> and <m>15</m>.</p>
                            <p>When <m>x=\highlight{-12}</m>:<md>
                                <mrow>\abs{x-3}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\abs{x+3}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\abs{\highlight{-12}-3}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\abs{\highlight{-12}+3}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\abs{-15}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\abs{-9}</mrow>
                                <mrow>15\amp\neq9</mrow>
                            </md>Since we had a false equation for our first value, we don't need to check the second input. The original equation is simply false.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
    </subsection>

