    <subsection>
        <title>Another Definition for Absolute Value</title>
        <p>We know <ellipsis/> how many definitions do we really need? But bear with us because this one is important.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Let's consider the function <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x^2}</m>. First, we will evaluate this function at a few arbitrary values: <m>3</m>, <m>0</m>, and <m>-5</m>.<md>
                    <mrow>f(\highlight{3})\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{3}^2}\amp f(\highlight{0})\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{0}^2}\amp f(\highlight{-5})\amp=\sqrt{(\highlight{-5})^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{9}\amp\amp=\sqrt{0}\amp\amp=\sqrt{25}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=3\amp\amp=0\amp\amp=5</mrow>
                </md>These results should be interesting: <m>f(3)=3</m>, <m>f(0)=0</m>, and <m>f(-5)=5</m>. The outputs are the same as the inputs, except for a missing negative sign on <m>5</m>. It seems like we've seen a function that does that exact same thing already <ellipsis/></p>
                <p>Make a quick graph using technology to see what the graph of <m>y=f(x)</m> looks like.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><xref ref="figure-square-root-of-square">Figure</xref> shows a graph of <m>f</m> where <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x^2}</m>. It looks just like the graph of <m>y=\abs{x}</m>.</p>

                <sidebyside widths="40% 56%" margins="0%">
                    <figure xml:id="figure-square-root-of-square">
                        <caption><m>y=\sqrt{x^2}</m></caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=sqrt(x^2) which looks exactly like the graph of y=abs(x). This looks like a V with the vertex of the V at the origin. The right hand side extends as a line with slope 1 and the left hand side extends with slope -1.</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-7,7) (0,0) (7,7)};
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <p>Since the graphs of <m>y=\sqrt{x^2}</m> and <m>y=\abs{x}</m> match up exactly, that must mean that <me>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</me> This idea will be used later in this chapter and it will continue to pop up in subsequent math courses here and there as an important topic.</p>
                </sidebyside>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the following expressions using the fact that <m>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</m>.</p>
                <p><ol label="a." cols="2">
                    <li><m>\sqrt{(x-2)^2}</m></li>
                    <li><m>\sqrt{x^6}</m></li>
                    <li><m>\sqrt{x^2+10x+25}</m></li>
                    <li><m>\sqrt{x^4}</m></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>\sqrt{(\highlight{x-2})^2}=\abs{\highlight{x-2}}</m>. Note that <m>\highlight{x-2}</m> might be a negative number depending on the value of <m>x</m>, so the absolute value will change those negative numbers to be positive values.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{x^6}\amp=\sqrt{(\highlight{x^3})^2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{\highlight{x^3}}</mrow>
                        </md>We know from exponent rules that <m>(x^3)^2=x^6</m>. Note that <m>\highlight{x^3}</m> will be negative whenever <m>x</m> is a negative number.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{x^2+10x+25}\amp=\sqrt{(\highlight{x+5})^2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{\highlight{x+5}}</mrow>
                        </md>Note again that <m>\highlight{x+5}</m> can be negative for certain values of <m>x</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{x^4}\amp=\sqrt{(\highlight{x^2})^2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{\highlight{x^2}}</mrow>
                        </md>Note here that since <m>\highlight{x^2}</m> is never negative (no matter what number you plug into <m>x^2</m>, you always either get a positive number or zero out), that the absolute value around <m>x^2</m> doesn't have anything to do. Absolute values change negative numbers to positive values but leave positive values alone. Thus, it is ok in this case to drop the absolute value symbols. The complete simplification is<ellipsis/><md>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{x^4}\amp=\sqrt{(\highlight{x^2})^2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{\highlight{x^2}}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=x^2</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Applications Involving Absolute Values</title>
        <p>Absolute values are quite useful as models in a variety of real world applications, many of which we will have the skills to cover at the end of the chapter. One easily understood example is the path of a billiards (pool) ball: when the ball bounces off one of the side rails, its path is mirrored and creates a <q>V</q> shape. The game gets more complicated when more than rail is hit, but the fundamental mathematics doesn't change: absolute values model the bounces each time. Here are some other introductory examples.</p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <sidebyside widths="42% 52%" margins="2%">
                    <p> When light reflects off of a mirror, the path it takes is in the shape of an absolute value graph. Khenbish was playing with a laser pointer in his bedroom mirror. He set up the laser pointer on his windowsill and the light hit the center of the mirror and reflected onto the corner of his room. He declared that the laser pointer is sitting at the origin, and <m>x</m> should stand for the horizontal distance from the left wall to the light beam. Shown is a birds-eye view of the situation.</p>

                    <figure xml:id="figure-laser-pointer">
                    <caption>Birds-Eye View of Khenbish's Room with Laser</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=5-5/4*abs(x-4), which looks like an upside down V with the vertex of the V at the point (4,5). The graph starts at the origin with a solid dot. The right hand side extends as a line with slope -5/4 with an arrow at (12,-5) and the left hand side extends with slope 5/4. There is a rectangle drawn with corners (0,-5), (0,5), (12,5), and (12,-5) representing the walls of the room. There are small rectangles near the origin representing the window sill and at the point (4,5) representing the mirrow.</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,xmax=13,ymin=-6,ymax=6,    xtick=\empty, minor xtick=\empty, ytick={-5,0,5}, minor ytick={-4,-2,...,4}, grid=none]
                                \addplot[color=secondcolor] coordinates{(0,-5)(0,5)(12,5)(12,-5)(0,-5)};
                                \addplot[fill=brown!20!white] coordinates{(0,-1)(0.2,-1)(0.2,1)(0,1)(0,-1)};
                                \addplot[fill=black!20!white] coordinates{(3.5,5)(3.5,4.95)(4.5,4.95)(4.5,5)(3.5,5)};
                                \addplot[-{Kite}, color=firstcolor, samples=151, domain=0:12] {5-(5/4)*abs(x-4)};
                                \addplot[only marks] coordinates{(0,0)};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>After a little bit of work, Khenbish was able to come up with a formula for the light's path: <me>d(x)=5-\frac{5}{4}\abs{x-4}</me> where <m>d(x)</m> stands for the distance above (for positive values) or below (for negatives) the center line through his room that represents the <m>x</m>-axis. Use a graph of this formula on technology to answer the following questions.</p>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>Khenbish's room is <m>10</m> feet wide according to the figure. What is the room's length?</p></li>
                    <li><p>How far along the wall is the mirror centered?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If you stood 9 feet from the left wall, how far above or below the room's center line (<m>x</m>-axis) should you stand to have the laser pointer hit you?</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                
                    <figure xml:id="figure-laser-pointer-detail">
                    <caption>Detailed Birds-Eye View of Khenbish's Room</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=5-5/4*abs(x-4), which looks like an upside down V with the vertex of the V at the point (4,5). The graph starts at the origin with a solid dot. The right hand side extends as a line with slope -5/4 with an arrow at (12,-5) and the left hand side extends with slope 5/4. There is a rectangle drawn with corners (0,-5), (0,5), (12,5), and (12,-5) representing the walls of the room. There are small rectangles near the origin representing the window sill and at the point (4,5) representing the mirrow.</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,xmax=13,ymin=-6,ymax=6,    xtick={0,1,...,12}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, minor ytick={-4,-2,...,4}, grid]
                                \addplot[color=secondcolor] coordinates{(0,-5)(0,5)(12,5)(12,-5)(0,-5)};
                                \addplot[fill=brown!20!white] coordinates{(0,-1)(0.2,-1)(0.2,1)(0,1)(0,-1)};
                                \addplot[fill=black!20!white] coordinates{(3.5,5)(3.5,4.95)(4.5,4.95)(4.5,5)(3.5,5)};
                                \addplot[-{Kite}, solid, color=firstcolor, samples=151, domain=0:12] {5-(5/4)*abs(x-4)};
                                \addplot[only marks] coordinates{(0,0)};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>

                    <p><ol>
                    <li><p>To find the room's length, first note that since the laser hits the corner of the room, the <m>x</m> coordinate of the lasers position would tell us the room's width. According to the detailed graph, the <m>x</m>-coordinate when <m>y=-5</m> is <m>12</m>. So the room must be <m>12</m> feet wide.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The mirror is centered exactly where the laser hits the wall. This is the vertex of the absolute value graph which, according to the graph, is at the point <m>(4,5)</m>. This tells us that the mirror is centered <m>4</m> feet from the left wall.</p></li>
                    <li><p>If you are standing 9 feet from the left wall, the laser's position will be a bit more than one foot behind the rooms center line, by the diagram. While technology can tell us the exact answer, here is how to do this problem algebraically.</p>
                    <p><md>
                        <mrow>d(\highlight{9})\amp=5-\frac{5}{4}\abs{\highlight{9}-4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-\frac{5}{4}\abs{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-\frac{5}{4}\cdot 5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-\frac{25}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-6.25</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-1.25</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                    <p>So, it looks like if you stand <m>9</m> feet from the left wall, you need to stand <m>1.25</m> feet behind the center line (which would be <m>6.25</m> feet from the wall with the mirror on it) to be hit by the laser.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>We do absolute value algebra in our heads any time someone says, <q>It should be so close of a certain value</q>. For example, <q>the board's length should be within a sixteenth of an inch of five inches long</q>. This statement means that the board might be as short as a sixteenth less than five inches, or as long as a sixteenth more than five inches.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>A persons temperature is considered <q>normal</q> if it is within half a degree Fahrenheit of <quantity><mag>98.6</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>. Mathematically can be stated using an absolute value. Let <m>T(x)=\abs{x-98.6}</m>, where <m>x</m> represents a person's temperature in degrees Fahrenheit and <m>T(x)</m> is the distance of that temperature from <quantity><mag>98.6</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>. If the value of <m>T(x)</m> is less than or equal to <m>0.5</m>, then the persons temperature is considered within normal range. Use the function <m>T</m> to decide about the following people's temperatures.</p>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>98.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, is that within normal range?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>99.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, is that within normal range?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>97.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, is that within normal range?</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>98.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, then we have<ellipsis/>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>T(\highlight{98.3})\amp=\abs{\highlight{98.3}-98.6}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{-0.3}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=0.3</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                        <p>Since the value of <m>T(98.3)</m> is a number smaller than <m>0.5</m>, then <quantity><mag>98.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> must be within normal range.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>99.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, then we have<ellipsis/>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>T(\highlight{99.3})\amp=\abs{\highlight{99.3}-98.6}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{0.7}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=0.7</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                        <p>Since the value of <m>T(99.3)</m> is a number bigger than <m>0.5</m>, then <quantity><mag>99.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> must <em>not</em> be within normal range.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>97.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, then we have<ellipsis/>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>T(\highlight{97.3})\amp=\abs{\highlight{97.3}-98.6}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{-1.3}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=1.3</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                        <p>Since the value of <m>T(97.3)</m> is a number bigger than <m>0.5</m>, then <quantity><mag>97.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> must <em>not</em> be within normal range.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The entryway to the Louvre Museum in Paris is through I.M. Pei's metal and glass Louvre Pyramid. This pyramid has a square base and is <m>71</m> feet high and <m>112</m> feet in width. The formula <m>h(x)=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{x-56}</m> gives the height above ground level of the pyramid at a distance of <m>x</m> from the left hand side of the pyramid base.</p>
                <sidebyside widths="42% 52%" margins="2%">
                    <figure xml:id="figure-Louvre-Pyramid">
                    <caption>A Diagram of the Front of the Louvre Pyramid</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=71-71/56*abs(x-56), which looks like an upside down V with the vertex of the V at the point (56,71). The graph exists between x=0 and x=112. The right hand side extends as a line with slope -71/56 and the left hand side extends with slope 71/56.</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xmin=-10,xmax=120,ymin=-10,ymax=80,    xtick={0,20,...,100}, minor xtick={0,10,...,110}, ytick={0,10,...,70}, minor ytick={0,5,...,75}, grid=none]
                                    \addplot[-, thick, color=fifthcolor, samples=99, domain=0:112] {71-(71/56)*abs(x-56)};
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                
                    <p><ol>
                        <li><p>If you are <m>20</m> feet from the left edge, how high will the pyramid rise in front of you? Round your result to the nearest tenth of an inch.</p></li>
                        <li><p>How far from the left edge is the center of the pyramid?</p></li>
                        <li><p>Using your previous answer, check that the formula gives you the correct height at the center.</p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>If you are <m>20</m> feet from the left edge, then <m>x</m> is <m>20</m>. Inputting that, we get<ellipsis/>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>h(\highlight{20})\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{\highlight{20}-56}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{-36}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\cdot 36</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 71-45.643</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 25.357</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 25.4</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    <p>The pyramid is about <m>25.4</m> feet high at the position <m>20</m> feet from the left edge.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The center of the pyramid is <m>56</m> feet from the either edge since it's half of <m>112</m> feet.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Inputting <m>56</m> into the formula for <m>h</m> gives us<ellipsis/>
                        <md>
                             <mrow>h(\highlight{56})\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{\highlight{56}-56}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{0}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\cdot 0</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    <p>And so the formula does give us the correct maximum height of <m>71</m> feet at the center of the pyramid.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
